ratings.question_text: Your level of engagement with the course was:
What is your overall assessment of this course?
The course was well organized to facilitate student learning.
I received clear feedback that improved my learning.
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the level of intellectual challenge of this course was:
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the workload of this course was:

narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Good knowledge of game theory topics. How game theory relates to politics.
I learned about static and dynamic games of complete and incomplete information.
I deepened my understanding of game theory in the context of politics. There were many real-world applications to the problems.

The course provided me with a pretty interesting theoretical toolkit for evaluating and finding equilibriums across a fairly wide set of games and ways of applying these theoretical toolkits to our political realities (which is a pretty interesting and helpful way of better understanding the mechanisms by which American politics operates).

This course introduced me to Game Theory and the various tools used to evaluate game theoretic questions, such as matrices and game trees. The class also taught me about some of the concepts used to formalize games, including the concept of a rational actor, utility, and actor preferences.
Learned how to think like a game theorist.
I learned about game theory in general and the basics of solving both static and sequential games.
Game theory, prison dilemma, baysian thinking and probabilities, multistep games and strategies, simultaneous games and subgames and sequential games
Basics of game theory.

A strong understanding of Nash equilibrium, in sequential and dynamic games, both with perfect & incomplete information. I also saw how these concepts applied to politics, like the median voter theorem and war theory.
I learned about the correlation between game theory and the real world, including numerous intriguing real-life political examples.
The basis of game theory and how to go about game analysis

I learned about stage and sequential games of complete and incomplete information. I learned how to solve game trees, normal form games, solve for various types of equilbria, and apply game theory logic to political science applications.
Intro to game theory, how to evaluate different types of games
i learned how to solve games

I learned how to solve different types of games (e.g., incomplete information, sequential games) and how the models we learned applied to public policy. I really enjoyed the practical focus of the class and now know some of the more formal game theory behind concepts like political accountability or the median voter theorem.
Basics of game theory (simultaneous, sequential, static, dynamic games) and their applications to political science

EP&E 295, in short, taught me how to map and solve the decision-making process of (political) actors in any of a number of situations with varying levels of information and decision sequences. For me, this class gave formulation to the considerations of these actors and demonstrated the various things for which they must account when making strategic decisions, such as player type and probability, sequence, and situational variation.
I got a basic understanding of static and sequential game theory games and complete and incomplete game theory games. I learned how to apply that knowledge in simple scenarios.
Learned about game theory and developed a basic understanding of it.

I learned a basic intuition about dynamic and static games of complete and incomplete information. The course really is divided into these four parts, and aside from a few political applications there are no other topics.
I learnt the essentials of game theory, and how to apply it to real-world political situations (a few)
Introductory game theory principles, a better understanding of political choice and choices in general, and better economic thinking
Basic game theory logic and how to solve 4 main types of problems in game theory.
Learned about different games and their application to poli sci. Course had an emphasis on finding different types of nash equilibria.
I was able to practice troubleshooting application of concepts. I learned how to evaluate situations based on theorizing actions.
Learned how to solve many game theory games
I developed skills in identifying the different types of games: dynamic, static, sequential, and simultaneous games, and how to find equilibrium in these games.

This was my first quantitative reasoning class at Yale so I learned the best strategies to employ when approaching Problem Sets. More specifically, I learned to apply the skills and problem solving skills taught in lectures to my personal completion of problem sets. I also gained further insight into how best to study for exams for future QR classes (ie. the usefulness of practice problems).
Interesting class, felt like a solid introduction to game theory.

I have a better understanding of game theory and how it applies in political situations that arise. I learned about how to conduct game theory probability and how it applies with the varying external factors associated with the complex situations of political ideas.
game theory
This course provided a solid introduction into the field of game theory. I learned game theory concepts and their application in the political science field.
A really strong understanding to intro game theory and how its applied in the real world.
I learned about general probability theory and statistics. I also learned about their applications in politics and political campaigns.

We began with the basics of game theory and learned about Nash equilibrium and game trees. As the semester moved on, we learned more complex topics like subgame equilibrium and games with incomplete information. We learned how to apply all these concepts to the political realm, most heavily focusing on electoral competitions.
My favorite things about this class was applying game theory to actual world scenarios--definitely gave me new insight into the Cold War, elections, and congressional agendas.
I gained a lot of insight on game theory: beginning with the basic game model and finding Pure Nash Equilibrium, then mixed strategy games, simultaneous games, and lastly Bayesian games.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Great course
Only strengths: Very logical structure, easy to understand lectures, great TFs and professor
The content is interesting and applicable to the real world. The workload was also very manageable.

I think game theory as a whole can have some pretty complex notation, but thats just a function of the field itself. I think the class did a good job for the most part of relaying information in lecture that we could then put into practice on the psets to work through the games ourselves. I think that structure is probably the best way of learning something like this. I also think Prof Turners a strength, as hes a really chill, friendly professor who is clearly very interested in what hes teaching and also appears to genuinely care about the students.

I thought that this course was very enjoyable overall! The class did a good job of teaching the basics of Game Theory in a way that was accessible for non-social science majors and those who had not taken college-level math. The class also had a manageable workload. The one weakness I found in the course was that there were not very many opportunities to practice some of the more conceptual problems (similar to the market for lemons example in class or backwards induction in unit 2) on the psets before the test.
Strengths: Professor Weaknesses: n/a

Strengths: fun, easy course that gets you excited about game theory. No exam, only 3 tests and PSets.

Weakness: not as in-depth as other game theory courses (like the economists one)

I think the class sometimes struggles with connecting the skills we are learning to the real world applications. There are classes about application in the real world but they are extremely complicated and hard to understand. I think a strength is that the TF's are really great and helpful, that is definitely the reason I passed.

The sections sometimes are hard to follow. Lectures are also, at least for me, hard to clearly follow the math, but going over it is actually fun and interesting to learn. Pset groups are good if you find people, grading isn't too strict. Tests are a little rushed because its only 50 minute class time, but just prepare well and the class will go well. And you won't (hopefully) get bored so you want to prepare well.

Strengths: accessibility to recordings, slides, and the full semester breakdown. The TF named Jen was amazing. If you can, get in her section. Non-cumulative 3 exams with no final. 
Weaknesses: sometimes went too fast. But if you go to Jen's section, she clears up things nicely so you know what exactly will be tested.
Can't really think of any points of improvement. Taught well, learned a lot! It could be easy to fall behind on the work, but that's a fault of the students, not the course.
The teaching style and structure of grading/assignments was well-organized and well-structured.
Maybe sections could be more intentional, it often felt like TFs didnt have a plan. Also, I feel like we could have used more practice problems.
I would have liked more real world examples

Strengths: Amazing TFs, the course was well-paced, exams and psets were very fair. 
Weaknesses: The lectures were sometimes very rushed. I think an easy fix would be to spend less time on the formal definitions of game theory topics, and focus the lectures on going through examples.
Strengths: very straightforward, tests matched psets and in-class material very well
The TFs were not often helpful  so there was a lot of self-learning and YouTube watching that took place.
i really liked this course. i liked that classes were recorded so i did not have to worry when i was sick. i wish there was more connections to present day political issues.

Prof. Turner is a very engaging lecturer, and the slides are also very clear. I also appreciated that the problem sets were straightforward and we were always taught the concepts we needed to know to complete them in class. Overall, I enjoyed lecture a lot and the class workload was very reasonable. Having a few more practice problems available might have been nice, since there wasnt too much beyond what we did for section.

This course is taught incredibly well - Prof Turner is very clear and the slides are very informative, which is great for exam prep. The problem sets were straightforward, but sections were still useful and the TAs were always helpful and frequently available. Genuinely interesting content also helps.

Like many introductory level economics classes, it followed an effective structure of problem sets to support learning in lecture over the course of the semester with greater learning benchmarks throughout the class. I appreciated the three smaller unit exams as opposed to, say, one midterm and one comprehensive final. In that way, I thought this class was more conducive to learning and retention than some other classes I've taken that follow a similar structure. As Professor Turner noted, what we learn at the any point in the class includes all or most of what we learned previous to it, so even if certain earlier subjects aren't explicitly tested, expertise in them is demonstrated by practicing those later subjects alone. In terms of improvement, there's nothing which sticks out to me as being in glaring need of revision. The only small critique I have is that, when it comes to studying for exams, it would be helpful to have practice problem sets, former exams, or just lists of questions as study aides. This was done at some points but not at others, and I think future students would benefit from it being a constant fixture in the course. If not only for practice, they would also help to give students a sense of what more abstract questions might look like to help reduce barriers to testing in general and, more specifically, the ability of people to demonstrate their knowledge.

It wasnt always the best organized. Pset problems disappeared after you submitted them which made it difficult to study for tests. And the answers for some psets werent always posted to help study for tests. The material in the lectures didnt seem to focus on what was in the psets. Many pset problems could only really be answered by those who went to office hours since the slides did not teach us how to answer the problems. There also wasnt much engagement with the political science portion of the class. Scenarios were talked about in lecture, but they rarely ever showed up on psets or exams.
professor was awesome. TAs answered all questions.

Strengths: the content itself is very interesting, specifically if you have never learned about game theory before. plenty of real world applications, including in day to day life you will start to notice the game theory at play

Weaknesses: Professor Turner often overcomplicates the material by delving too deeply into the math of certain examples without first explaining the big picture.

It's an easy class, and the Professor's slides are really clear about the material. Unfortunately, this means you don't have to attend class to do well (I didn't go after the first midterm.) There is no final, and the three midterms are easy to do well on. Take this class for a more chill introduction to Game Theory!

Strengths: Jen the TF/office hours! The timeline of the class was well spread out, made it very easy to follow, the lectures are pretty solid and digestible for the most part if you do the readings, prof is cool and chill
Weaknesses: sometimes the lecture does get a little too tricky to understand at times when it gets to the more complex and sometimes there isn't a similar problem from lecture that's on the psets, also there is not a lot of material to use to study for exams so it feels a bit like you're in the dark until you've gotten through an exam or two which makes them a bit more stressful than they need to be

The course is very well-structured. Professor Turner is engaging and thorough. The only improvement I might suggest would be resources for further practice problems outside those in the recommended textbook; they're easy to find online, so it's not a huge setback at all.

Office hours with TFs were at super inconvenient times when a lot of students had classes. I wish we had been given more access to practice problems and guidance as to what exactly in the textbook to read. A lot of the chapters we read had stuff in it that when I asked the TFs, they would say we didnt actually need to know that, but it was in the syllabus.

The PSETs and sections were really beneficial for learning. Lectures could be improved by slowing their pace down a little. It might be better to cover fewer examples and just take it slower. This didn't end up being too much of a problem because of sections though.

Strengths: Course is organized. TAs are great. I liked how the course was broken up into units.
Weaknesses: political science concepts seemed disjointed from the game theory concepts we were learning. I think a final project, where we apply the concepts we learned to the real world, would have been more engaging and fulfilling than a third exam.
The discussion section associated with the lecture was very helpful in grounding an understanding in topics.

Strengths: Amazing TFs (shout out to Jen)

Weaknesses: I think lectures could go more systematically through how to solve games (thinking like white boards, talking it through) because easier to see like a professor solve a game to understand how to do it

Strengths: timed very well, each game was thoroughly explained and detailed
Weakness: the connection to political science aspects were extremely abstract and different to understand

Strengths: Solving problems was integrated into the lectures so we would learn topics conceptually then immediately apply them. Professor Turner was super enthusiastic which made for a very engaging lecture. Problem sets were the right amount of challenge  they didnt feel impossible but required critical thinking and application beyond super simply problems. 
Weaknesses: It was unclear how much information we needed to retain from the textbook.

The strengths of this course was the professor along with the structure of the course overall. The only weakness I could think of is the timing in between exams seems to be a little condensed at times and the sections were not incredibly helpful in understanding content.
no, the course is brilliant

One of the strengths of this course is its organization. Professor Turner and the teaching team are very organized and make it very easy for students to stay on track throughout the course. The pace of the class is also very digestible and easy to follow. I also preferred the format of the class being split up into thirds, with three exams testing our knowledge after each unit.

Turner is an amazing lecturer and has clear, well organized slides. The psets and exams are very fair and not trying to trick you. The only weakness is that there are not many practice questions for the tests (the only practice question material is from the psets)
Strengths included the approachability of both the teaching assistants and the professor. Weaknesses include the inability to engage in in-class lectures

The professor is very engaging and great at explaining complicated topics in a way that is easy for everyone to understand. However, the course description says there is no math beyond algebra needed and although that is mostly true, it does help to have some knowledge of calculus. The TFs are not very helpful.

Strengths - Professor Turner is a very engaging lecturer and the content was pretty interesting 

Weaknesses - Both TFs were not very good at explaining things during section or office hours

The curriculum was very well structured, increasing in complexity and rigor and building on knowledge from the beginning of the class. An improvement should be to increase the practice material we have before the exams. It would be extremely beneficial to have practice exams before the exam instead of merely redoing psets.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes.
I would recommend this course to another student as I learned a lot and it wasn't extremely stressful.
I would recommend this course to another student because it is pretty straightforward and it doesn't take up too much time.

Yes. I think the course provides you with a useful and interesting theoretical toolkit for evaluating games, and the policy applications we talk about in class add depth and utility to what you learn. If you get really frustrated by really involved notation, its possible youll get frustrated around the middle of the semester, and you should be aware that everything in the course really does build upon itself and compound in difficulty as you go along, so make sure you understand each concept before you move past it, but otherwise its a really chill class with a nice professor, easy grading, and interesting/useful material.
I would recommend this class because the content was very interesting and the course gave me a solid introduction to Game Theory.
100%. Prof. Ian Turner was a fantastic professor, who made the topic of game theory and its applications very interesting and fun to go to class.
Yes, if you want a gut game theory course.

I think if you are interested in learning what game theory is and you need a QR credit this is a good class. I did find it pretty challenging at first. It takes time to learn but once you get the hang of it you'll be fine. I did enjoy the class once I got over the initial learning curve.
Yes, it's probably less math heavy compared to the straight econ game theory class and it applies to some political aspects. Its a good class to take and you probably won't regret it.

Yes! Ian is great and so are the TFs. 7 PSETS, 3 non-cumulative exams, no final. I learned a LOT with relatively low stress. I suggest making a study group for checking the PSETs and just make sure to study well for the 3 exams. A tip would be to take notes on an iPad or device so you can just download the slides and write notes on the slides (sometimes the slides are filled with a lot of info and NOT enough time to copy everything down).
Great QR!
Yes, due to the great teaching and the great structure of the course.

I learned a lot about the principles of game theory and how to apply them to political situations. I enjoyed doing the problems and solving for equilibria. I also liked thinking through applications of the principles to political science situations. I have a thorough understanding of game theory.
Yes! This course is a great way to get an introduction to game theory
Yes! If you like political science topics like median voter theory and want to understand how to apply economics topics to the real world - I would definitely recommend this course.
yes i would i learned a lot.

Yes! This is an engaging introduction to game theory that focuses a lot on political applications of the theory and has a very reasonable workload. If you really enjoy the nuances of game theory or want to play games in class, you might prefer Econ 159, but this is a great class.

Yes! Very well organized and clearly taught, interesting content and applications, great professor and straightforward problem sets. I previously dropped 159 because I would have to spend hours in office hours, and this course was significantly more accessible and fun.

I would definitely recommend this course to other students and frankly already have. I think that, above all, EP&E 295 is one of the few classes which I've taken at Yale that explicitly emphasizes and puts a premium on the actual learning of the material rather than mere test preparation. Between that and what I've already mentioned, this class merits a look by anyone.
It is a less intense way of learning game theory than the main game theory course. So I would recommend it for students looking for that.
yeah, good intro course to game theory

I would not recommend this course -- if you have to take game theory, or if you want to, take ECON 159. Even if it's slightly harder, it will teach you the material much more effectively. For this class you essentially have to learn the material yourself.

Take this as a breadth requirement for the cognitive science major for a chill semester and a pretty good introduction to Game Theory if you don't feel like going too far into the nitty gritties of the subject.

Yes, definitely a great option for your game theory requirements or voluntary interest, lectures are only 50 min (more digestible) and the 3 exam and no final system is epic. The psets are solidly reasonable and the media library of lectures is clutch for confusing topics. This was a very accessible class and made life straightforward compared to most yale courses which was appreciated. Small lecture in the afternoon is also nice
Yes, this is a fantastic class to take in order to get a good introduction of Game Theory as a discipline
Yes. It's a great course for students that aren't seeking a math-heavy semester to fulfill a QR requirement and develop logical reasoning in a powerful way.
Yes, but I wouldnt say its a super easy course.
Yes, it really helps you understand game theory when it comes up in other aspects of political science.
Only if you have to take it.
I would recommend this course to another student. While at first the course can come across as challenging, after more time engaging with the topics, it becomes easier to follow.
Yes, it was a great introduction to game theory and the professor was great at teaching it

Yes! Im not an EP&E major but I still really enjoyed this course and feel like Im walking away with a useful skillset. The course never felt completely impossible but I consistently felt the right amount of challenge.
Yes. Interesting, well taught, reasonable workload.
Yes I would, because I think it offers valuable insights into the minds of people and how game theory plays out in real-life situations.
yes, because it is a nice and moderately difficult course that rewards those who treat it seriously.

I would definitely recommend this class to other students, especially those looking to fill their EPE prereq. It is a well taught class on an interesting topic with a fairly light workload. the three exams are fair, if you put in some studying.
YES! Turner explains the material incredibly clearly and the exams and psets are very fair.
Yes, it is such a good gut and just based on psets and three exams that were easy to study for and not cumulative.

I would recommend this course if you are interested in learning the basics of game theory and how it can be applied to political situations. If you are just looking for an easy QR, I wouldn't say this is the course for you. However, it is very interesting and engaging.

If the student needs this course as a prereq then sure. If this student wants to take a course on game theory, I recommend a different game theory course. If the student needs a QR and doesn't know much about game theory, I recommend a different course.
I would recommend this course, as it is an intellectually simulating way to gain one's QR credit while being exposed to different applications of math.
Yes--if you are taking it as a QR credit like me, it is pretty interesting and not too math-heavy.

I would recommend this course as it is a good introduction to game theory as well as it provides insight on how game theory could be applied in real life politics. The professor is very enthusiastic to help and answer questions and lectures are recorded so you can re-watch in case you don't understand something in class.
